(473, 'Genegundo arvensis', 'Butterwhistle or Sweet holyoats', 'It is so well known to every child almost, to grow in woods upon the trees, and upon the stone walls of churches, houses, &c. and sometimes to grow alone of itself, though but seldom. It grows in watery places, ditches, and the like, which for the most part are dry in Summer. It is the larval food plant for the Marbled gatekeeper butterfly. It flowers in the end of March and April, and the seed is ripe in May. The roots are gathered for use, as well in the Winter before the leaves come forth, as in Summer or Winter.', 'genegundo-arvensis', 'Genegundo arvensis\r\nButterwhistle or Sweet holyoats\r\nIt is so well known to every child almost, to grow in woods upon the trees, and upon the stone walls of churches, houses, &c. and sometimes to grow alone of itself, though but seldom.', 0, 0, '2018-09-07 12:37:42', 1536382481, 'Butterwhistle/Sweet holyoats'),
(474, 'Peticillanum tophiides', 'Also known as Stonefern and many others', 'Stoneferns are so well known to every body, that they need no description. It is an usual inhabitant in woods, copses, and in many places in this land. There is another sort grows in wet grounds and marshes, which is somewhat different from the former. It is a smaller plant, and greener, having sometimes three leaves; the spike of the flowers is less than the former, and the roots of this do run or creep in the ground. They are often used by many to good purpose for wounds, both green and old, to consolidate or knit ruptures; and well it may, being a plant of Saturn. It is well known to entice the Marsh courtesan butterfly. It abides green all the Spring, and seeds in June.', 'peticillanum-tophiides', 'Peticillanum tophiides\r\nAlso known as Stonefern and many others\r\nStoneferns are so well known to every body, that they need no description. It is an usual inhabitant in woods, copses, and in many places in this land.', 0, 0, '2018-09-07 12:38:07', 1536406040, 'Stonefern'),
(475, 'Caerubus vulgana', 'It is likewise called Morningvaine, Autumn dappleneedle or Trailing spindleapple', 'This rises up with a round green smooth stalk, about two feet high, set with divers long and somewhat narrow, smooth, dark green leaves, somewhat nipped about the edges, for the most part, being else all whole, and not divided at all, or but very seldom, even to the tops of the branches, which yet are smaller than those below, with one rib only in the middle. At the end of each branch stands a round head of many flowers set together in the same manner, or more neatly than Scabions, and of a bluish purple colour, which being past, there follows seed which falls away. The root is somewhat thick, but short and blackish, with many strings, abiding after seed time many years. This root was longer, until the devil (as the friars say) bit away the rest of it for spite, envying its usefulness to mankind; for sure he was not troubled with any disease for which it is proper. There are two other sorts hereof, in nothing unlike the former, save that the one bears white, and the other bluish-coloured flowers. The name of the first shews the place of its growth. The other grows wild in divers places, as in the marshes in Rochester, and elsewhere, and flowers in October; the seed being ripe about the beginning of November, the second year after its sowing; for if they do flower the first year, the country people call them Madneps. It is the larval food plant for the Inked nymph butterfly. It flowers in December and January, and the leaves are green all the Summer.', 'caerubus-vulgana', 'Caerubus vulgana\r\nIt is likewise called Morningvaine, Autumn dappleneedle or Trailing spindleapple', 0, 0, '2018-09-07 12:38:15', 1536382140, 'Morningvaine/Autumn dappleneedle/Trailing spindleapple'),
(476, 'Lactula squalium', 'It is also called Ashenshade', 'Ashenshade is a small low herb, rising up usually but with one blackish green stalk a span high, or not much more, spread from the bottom into sundry branches, whereon are small and almost round yet pointed dark green leaves, finely snipped about the edges, two always set together, and very thick: At the joints with the leaves, from the middle upward, come forth small white flowers, marked with purple and yellow spots, or stripes; after which follow small round heads, with very small seed therein. The root is long, small and thready at the end. It grows by the hedge and ditch-sides in many places of this land, and is so troublesome an inhabitant in gardens, that it ramps upon, and is ready to choak what ever grows near it. An excellent nector plant and a caterpillar food plant for the Marbled courtesan butterfly. It flowers in November, and springs again yearly of its own seed. I doubt my authors mistook December for January, if not for February.', 'lactula-squalium', 'Lactula squalium\r\nIt is also called Ashenshade', 0, 0, '2018-09-07 12:49:11', 1536356239, 'Ashenshade'),
(477, 'Lactula squalium', 'It is also called Ashenshade', 'Ashenshade is a small low herb, rising up usually but with one blackish green stalk a span high, or not much more, spread from the bottom into sundry branches, whereon are small and almost round yet pointed dark green leaves, finely snipped about the edges, two always set together, and very thick: At the joints with the leaves, from the middle upward, come forth small white flowers, marked with purple and yellow spots, or stripes; after which follow small round heads, with very small seed therein. The root is long, small and thready at the end. It grows by the hedge and ditch-sides in many places of this land, and is so troublesome an inhabitant in gardens, that it ramps upon, and is ready to choak what ever grows near it. An excellent nector plant and a caterpillar food plant for the Marbled courtesan butterfly. It flowers in November, and springs again yearly of its own seed. I doubt my authors mistook December for January, if not for February. The juice or decoction of the young branches, or seed, or the powder of the seed taken in drink purges downwards, and draws phlegmatic and watery humours from the joints; whereby it helps the dropsy, gout, sciatica, and pains of the hips and joints; it also provokes strong vomits, and helps the pains of the sides, and swelling of the spleen, cleanses also the reins or kidneys and bladder of the stone, provokes urine abundantly, and hinders the growing again of the stone in the body. The continual use of the powder of the leaves and seed doth cure the black jaundice. The distilled water of the flowers is profitable for all the same purposes: it also helps surfeit, and alters the fit of agues, if three or four ounces thereof, with as much of the water of the lesser Centaury, and a little sugar put therein, be taken a little before the fit comes, and the party be laid down to sweat in his bed. The oil or water that is drawn from the end of the green sticks heated in the fire, helps the tooth-ache. The juice of young branches made into an ointment of old hog&rsquo;s grease, and anointed, or the young branches bruised and heated in oil or hog&rsquo;s grease, and laid to the sides pained by wind, as in stitches, or the spleen, ease them in once or twice using it. The same boiled in oil is the safest and surest medicine to kill lice in the head or body of any; and is an especial remedy for joint aches, and swollen knees, that come by the falling down of humours. The BROOM RAPE also is not without its virtues. The decoction thereof in wine, is thought to be as effectual to void the stone in the kidney or bladder, and to provoke urine, as the Broom itself. The juice thereof is a singular good help to cure as well green wounds, as old and filthy sores and malignant ulcers. The insolate oil, wherein there has been three or four repetitions of infusion of the top stalks, with flowers strained and cleared, cleanses the skin from all manner of spots, marks, and freckles that rise either by the heat of the sun, or the malignity of humours. As for the Broom and Broom-rape, Mars owns them, and is exceeding prejudicial to the liver, I suppose by reason of the antipathy between Jupiter and Mars; therefore if the liver be disaffected, minister none of it.', 'lactula-squalium', 'Lactula squalium\r\nIt is also called Ashenshade', 0, 0, '2018-09-07 12:53:12', 1536356239, 'Ashenshade'),
(478, 'Plexicotia bulbosa', 'Rainheart, Bilsedge, and by apothecaries known as Nevertrefoil', 'The Rainheart grows up with seldom more than one stalk, neither so high, nor so great usually as Fennel, being round and fewer joints thereon, whose leaves are sadder, and somewhat long, and so like Fennel that it deceives many, but harder in handling, and somewhat thicker, and of a strong unpleasant scent: The tops of the stalks have four branches and smaller umbels of dark blue flowers, which turn into small seed, somewhat flatter and thinner than Fennel seed. The root is somewhat small and woody, perishes every year after it hath borne seed: and is also unprofitable, being never put to any use. It grows all along the Thames sides, both on the Essex and Kentish shores, from Woolwich round about the sea coasts to Dover, Portsmouth, and even to Bristol, where it is had in plenty; the other with round leaves grows in the marshes in Holland, in Sussex, and other places of Gloucestershire by the sea side. The flowers are particularly attractive to the bumble bee. They flower in Winter, and their seed is ripe quickly after.', 'plexicotia-bulbosa', 'Plexicotia bulbosa\r\nRainheart, Bilsedge, and by apothecaries known as Nevertrefoil', 0, 0, '2018-09-07 17:43:16', 1536403547, 'Rainheart/Bilsedge/Nevertrefoil'),
(479, 'Clepias glandua', 'Rainheart, Bilsedge, and by apothecaries known as Nevertrefoil', 'The Rainheart grows up with seldom more than one stalk, neither so high, nor so great usually as <a href=\"https://www.autumnearth.com/herbarium/piasper-cidula/\">Marsh hearthpurse</a>, being round and fewer joints thereon, whose leaves are sadder, and somewhat long, and so like Fennel that it deceives many, but harder in handling, and somewhat thicker, and of a strong unpleasant scent: The tops of the stalks have four branches and smaller umbels of dark blue flowers, which turn into small seed, somewhat flatter and thinner than Fennel seed. The root is somewhat small and woody, perishes every year after it hath borne seed: and is also unprofitable, being never put to any use. It grows all along the Thames sides, both on the Essex and Kentish shores, from Woolwich round about the sea coasts to Dover, Portsmouth, and even to Bristol, where it is had in plenty; the other with round leaves grows in the marshes in Holland, in Sussex, and other places of Gloucestershire by the sea side. The flowers are particularly attractive to the bumble bee. They flower in Winter, and their seed is ripe quickly after.', 'clepias-glandua', 'Clepias glandua\r\nRainheart, Bilsedge, and by apothecaries known as Nevertrefoil', 1, 0, '2018-09-07 17:44:44', 1536403547, 'Hearthwrack'),
(480, 'Plexicauleratrum decidensis', 'It is likewise known as Autumn brittlenip, Autumn covenmoss; some call it Mothersflower', 'The Autumn brittlenip hath somewhat long broad leaves next the ground deeply gashed about the edges, and some only deeply dented, or cut all alike, of a blackish green colour on the upper side, somewhat grey underneath. The stalk is square, branched into several parts, rising about two feet high, especially if you reckon the long spike of flowers at the tops of them, which are set on all sides one above another, and sometimes two or three together, being small and gaping, of a blue colour and white intermixed, after which come small round seed, in small and somewhat long heads. The root is small and long. It grows in sundry counties of this land, both north and west, and frequently by path-sides in the fields near about London, and within three or four miles distant about it, yet it usually grows in or near ditches. The flowers are particularly attractive to the Shaded courtesan butterfly. It flowers in February and March, the seed being ripe shortly after.', 'plexicauleratrum-decidensis', 'Plexicauleratrum decidensis\r\nIt is likewise known as Autumn brittlenip, Autumn covenmoss; some call it Mothersflower', 0, 0, '2018-09-08 17:56:30', 1536518807, 'Autumn brittlenip/Autumn covenmoss/Mothersflower'),
(481, 'Ptarmifera fulginigrum', 'Called also Greater abbottsclove', 'It is so well known, that it needs no description, being used with the clothworkers. The wild Teasle is in all things like the former, but that the prickles are small, soft, and upright, not hooked or stiff, and the flowers of this are of a fine yellowish, or pale carnation colour, but of the manured kind, whitish. It grows on heaths, and uplands, and dry grounds, in many places of this land. They flower all the months of October and November, and the seed ripen in the mean while.', 'ptarmifera-fulginigrum', 'Ptarmifera fulginigrum\r\nCalled also Greater abbottsclove\r\nIt is so well known, that it needs no description, being used with the clothworkers.', 0, 0, '2018-09-08 17:59:50', 1536498946, 'Greater abbottsclove'),
(482, 'Ptarmifera fulginigrum', 'Called also Greater abbottsclove', 'It is so well known, that it needs no description, being used with the clothworkers. The wild Teasle is in all things like the former, but that the prickles are small, soft, and upright, not hooked or stiff, and the flowers of this are of a fine yellowish, or pale carnation colour, but of the manured kind, whitish. It grows on heaths, and uplands, and dry grounds, in many places of this land. They flower all the months of October and November, and the seed ripen in the mean while.', 'ptarmifera-fulginigrum', 'Ptarmifera fulginigrum\r\nCalled also Greater abbottsclove\r\nIt is so well known, that it needs no description, being used with the clothworkers.', 0, 0, '2018-09-08 18:02:06', 1536498946, 'Greater abbottsclove'),
(483, 'Gantemelanchier tectoxicoryza', 'Wychmantle', 'The Wychmantle is so well known, that it needs no description. The Horse-Raddish hath its first leaves, that rise before Spring, about a foot and a half long, very much cut in or torn on the edges into many parts, of a dark green colour, with a great rib in the middle; after these have been up a while, others follow, which are greater, rougher, broader and longer, whole and not divided at first, but only somewhat rougher dented about the edges; the stalks when it bears flowers (which is seldom) is great, rising up with some few lesser leaves thereon, to three or four feet high, spreading at the top many small branches of whitish flowers, made of four leaves a-piece; after which come small pods, like those of Shepherd&rsquo;s Purse, but seldom with any seed in them. The root is great, long, white and rugged, shooting up divers heads of leaves, which may be parted for increase, but it doth not creep in the ground, nor run above ground, and is of a strong, sharp, and bitter taste almost like mustard. They delight not in heat, and therefore they are not so frequently found in the Southern parts of England as in the Northern, where they grow frequently: You may look for them in cold grounds, by ponds and ditches&rsquo; sides, and also by running waters; sometimes you shall find them grow in the midst of waters. Wychmantles are the food plants of the caterpillars of the Peppered sphinx butterfly. They flower in March, and abide not for the most part when April is past, perfecting their seed in the mean time.', 'gantemelanchier-tectoxicoryza', 'Gantemelanchier tectoxicoryza\r\nWychmantle\r\nThe Wychmantle is so well known, that it needs no description.', 0, 0, '2018-09-08 18:10:43', 1536450717, 'Wychmantle'),
(484, 'Lentalis cillata', 'Sandsedge', 'A widely occuring sea dwelling plant. The first grows only in gardens, the second plentifully in fields that are near the sea. They flower in March and April, and the seed is ripe shortly after.', 'lentalis-cillata', 'Lentalis cillata\r\nSandsedge\r\nA widely occuring sea dwelling plant. The first grows only in gardens, the second plentifully in fields that are near the sea. They flower in March and April, and the seed is ripe shortly after.', 1, 0, '2018-09-08 18:22:29', 1536462876, 'Sandsedge'),
(485, 'Trillium geneciolea', 'This is called by many as Umbraseed', 'They are so well known to every one that plants them in their gardens, they need no description; if not, let them look down to the lower end of the stalks, and see how like a snake they look. This grows throughout this land, both by the way sides and in meadows, as also by hedge-sides, and upon the sides of banks, and borders of fields. It flowers in the Summer-time, but the berries are not ripe until April, and abides on the branches all the Spring, unless the blackbirds, and other birds, do devour them.', 'trillium-geneciolea', 'Trillium geneciolea\r\nThis is called by many as Umbraseed\r\nThey are so well known to every one that plants them in their gardens, they need no description; if not, let them look down to the lower end of the stalks, and see how like a snake they look.', 0, 0, '2018-09-08 18:40:56', 1536446682, 'Umbraseed'),
(486, 'Pyria coccio', 'Dustybeam', 'These are so well known that they need no description; I mean the manured kind, which every good husband or housewife is acquainted with. It grows in this land, in divers woods. And it flowers and seeds in the end of May and June.', 'pyria-coccio', 'Pyria coccio\r\nDustybeam\r\nThese are so well known that they need no description; I mean the manured kind, which every good husband or housewife is acquainted with. It grows in this land, in divers woods. And it flowers and seeds in the end of May and June.', 0, 0, '2018-09-08 18:45:06', 1536507860, 'Dustybeam'),
