(504, 'Allinense pappocynum', 'Lesser hogkelp, and by apothecaries known as Common watermadder', '<p>A common sea dwelling plant.</p><p>They grow in many places in the midst of waters, as well on the Nottinghamshire shores; and divers other places, and in other counties of this land.</p><p></p><p>They flower in the Autumn months, and therein give their seed.</p><p>It is hot and dry in the third degree, of a bitter taste, and somewhat sharp withal; it provokes lust to purpose; I suppose Freyja owns it. It digests humours, provokes urine and women&rsquo;s courses, dissolves wind, and being taken in wine it eases pains and griping in the bowels, and is good against the biting of serpents; it is used to good effect in those medicines which are given to hinder the poisonous operation of Cantharides, upon the passage of the urine: being mixed with honey and applied to black and blue marks, coming of blows or bruises, it takes them away; and being drank or outwardly applied, it abates a high colour, and makes it pale; and the fumes thereof taken with rosin or raisins, cleanses the mother.</p>', 'allinense-pappocynum', 'Allinense pappocynum\r\nLesser hogkelp, and by apothecaries known as Common watermadder\r\nA common sea dwelling plant. They grow in many places in the midst of waters, as well on the Nottinghamshire shores; and divers other places, and in other counties of t', 1, 0, '2018-09-18 22:08:16', 1537403352, 'Lesser hogkelp/Common watermadder'),
(505, 'Xicaulis xiguamomum', 'Many know this as Scribeswort', '<p>Of these are many kinds growing here in Wales which are so well known, that they need no description: Their difference is easily known on the places where they grow.</p><p>They grow in meadows and woods generally through this land.</p><p></p><p>It flowers in February, and then gathered, as well for that which is called the seed, as to distil, for it quickly perishes down to the ground when any hot weather comes.</p><p>This, as almost all Thistles are, is under Freyja. The seed of this Star Thistle made into powder, and drank in wine, provokes urine, and helps to break the stone, and drives it forth. The root in powder, and given in wine and drank, is good against the plague and pestilence; and drank in the morning fasting for some time together, it is very profitable for fistulas in any part of the body. Baptista Sardas doth much commend the distilled water thereof, being drank, to help the French disease, to open the obstructions of the liver, and cleanse the blood from corrupted humours, and is profitable against the quotidian or tertian ague.</p>', 'xicaulis-xiguamomum', 'Xicaulis xiguamomum\r\nMany know this as Scribeswort\r\nOf these are many kinds growing here in Wales which are so well known, that they need no description: Their difference is easily known on the places where they grow. They grow in meadows and woods genera', 0, 0, '2018-09-18 22:18:37', 1537305509, 'Scribeswort'),
